David M. Schwarz (born 1941 in [[Los Angeles]]) is an American architect.

The architectural office David M. Schwarz Architects, Inc. was established in 1976 in [[Washington, D.C.]]. Schwarz received his bachelor's degree from [[St. John's College (Annapolis/Santa Fe)|St. John's College]] in [[Annapolis, Maryland]], and a master of architecture from [[Yale University]]. He serves as the chairman of the [[Yale School of Architecture]] Dean's Council.<ref>[http://interactive.wttw.com/schwarz/timeline David M. Schwarz Career Timeline], WTTW Street Smarts</ref>

Schwarz is known for various high-profile [[New Urbanism]] projects and [[New Classical architecture|New Classical]] building designs.<ref>[http://interactive.wttw.com/schwarz/biography Short Biography: David M. Schwarz], Street Smarts</ref> He received the renowned [[Driehaus Architecture Prize]] on 21 March 2015 in [[Chicago]].<ref>[http://news.nd.edu/news/55213-david-m-schwarz-named-2015-richard-h-driehaus-prize-laureate/ David M. Schwarz named 2015 Richard H. Driehaus Prize laureate], Notre Dame University news</ref><ref>[http://www.archdaily.com/587976/david-m-schwarz-named-2015-driehaus-prize-laureate/ David M. Schwarz Named 2015 Driehaus Prize Laureate], ArchDaily, 15 January 2015</ref>

==Work==
[[File:Schermerhorn.jpg|thumb|New Classical [[Schermerhorn Symphony Center]] in [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]], completed in 2006]]
Notable architectural projects by David M. Schwarz include (chron.):<ref>[http://www.dmsas.com/#/portfolio DMSAS Portfolio]</ref>
*The Westbrook, [[Fort Worth]], Texas, USA (2013)
*Alpharetta City Hall, [[Alpharetta, Georgia]], USA (2012)
*[[Sundance Square]], [[Fort Worth]], Texas, USA (2010)
*Gaillard Center, [[Charleston, South Carolina]], USA (2010)
*[[Smith Center for the Performing Arts]], [[Las Vegas]], Nevada, USA (2007)
*Palladium at the Center for the Performing Arts ([[Carmel Symphony Orchestra]]), [[Carmel, Indiana]], USA (2006)
*[[Schermerhorn Symphony Center]], [[Nashville, Tennessee]], USA (2006)
*[[Sid Richardson Museum]], [[Fort Worth]], Texas, USA (2006)
*[[Firewheel Town Center]], [[Garland, Texas]], USA (2005)
*[[National Cowgirl Museum and Hall of Fame]], [[Fort Worth]], Texas, USA (2002)
*[[American Airlines Center]], [[Dallas]], Texas, USA (2001)
*[[Nancy Lee and Perry R. Bass Performance Hall]], [[Fort Worth]], Texas, USA (1996)
*1201 F Street NW, [[Washington, D.C.]], USA (1990)
*1718 Connecticut Avenue NW, [[Washington, D.C.]], USA (1979)

